{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d795a954-aa8a-41c6-bbd3-53e499326658","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace** (e.g., 30 seconds):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to speedscope format for browser-based viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n# Then open at https://speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or the `createdump`/`dotnet-monitor` approach instead.\n- For production, consider [`dotnet-monitor`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces on demand without exec'ing in.\n- `--profile cpu-sampling` is lightweight and safe for production use.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f3a16b2e-10cf-4c08-a8d8-3ae5019cbb49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question that doesn't require code changes or tool usage - I can answer from knowledge.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"D7C6:100995:EFEA82:112A28E:69F2B077"},"id":"eaa933af-1715-490b-a692-330c9cbe992b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:29:38.561Z","parentId":"d3de21fd-1d3b-47d7-b385-8b18c9b80ea5"}
